igd Koninkrijk","Chartley, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1332–":"about 1332–Deceased","1282–1350":"1282–1350","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1332–Female":"1332–Deceased","1411":"1411","Abt 1332":"about 1332","1332":"1332","1350":"1350","1282":"1282","Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chartley, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ferrers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire (Eure) and Ferrières (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferris","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Ó Fearghuis</b> or <b>Ó Fearghasa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fearghus</i>’, or from the Scottish-Gaelic form of this personal name, <i>Fearghus</i> (see   Fergus  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure and Ferrières, La Manche in Normandy, France."]},{"name":"Ferridge","meanings":["English: unexplained; possibly a form of  <i>Ferris</i> and therefore a variant of   Ferrers  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Ferrers was born about 1332, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married John de Kynnardsleye Jr. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1332–":"umbes 1332–Surnud","1282–1350":"1282–1350","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1332–Female":"1332–Surnud","1411":"1411","Abt 1332":"umbes 1332","1332":"1332","1350":"1350","1282":"1282","Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chartley, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1332–":"noin 1332–Kuollut","1282–1350":"1282–1350","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1332–Female":"1332–Kuollut","1411":"1411","Abt 1332":"noin 1332","1332":"1332","1350":"1350","1282":"1282","Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chartley, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningas